    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-heading mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4 mb-12">
      <details class="group border border-border rounded-xl">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer font-semibold text-heading text-sm flex justify-between items-center">
          Does longer content get cited more?
          <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm text-text-muted leading-relaxed">Not necessarily. Length matters less than structure. A well-structured 500-word FAQ page gets cited more than a 5,000-word blog post with no clear answers. AI needs extractable content, not volume.</div>
      </details>
      <details class="group border border-border rounded-xl">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer font-semibold text-heading text-sm flex justify-between items-center">
          Should I stop writing blog posts?
          <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm text-text-muted leading-relaxed">No. Blog posts serve other purposes (thought leadership, SEO, audience building). But if your goal is AI citations specifically, restructure blog content to lead with answers and use clear headings.</div>
      </details>
      <details class="group border border-border rounded-xl">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer font-semibold text-heading text-sm flex justify-between items-center">
          Do tables really help AI citations?
          <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm text-text-muted leading-relaxed">Yes. Comparison tables are one of the most cited formats because AI can parse structured data easily. Tables with clear headers and consistent formatting are particularly effective.</div>
      </details>
      <details class="group border border-border rounded-xl">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer font-semibold text-heading text-sm flex justify-between items-center">
          What is answer-first content?
          <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm text-text-muted leading-relaxed">Content that puts the direct answer to the question in the first sentence or paragraph, then expands with context, evidence and detail. Most traditional content does the opposite, building up to the answer.</div>
      </details>
      <details class="group border border-border rounded-xl">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 cursor-pointer font-semibold text-heading text-sm flex justify-between items-center">
          Can I convert existing content into citation-friendly formats?
          <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm text-text-muted leading-relaxed">Yes. Adding an FAQ section to existing pages, restructuring paragraphs to lead with answers, and adding comparison tables are all ways to improve citation potential without rewriting everything.</div>
      </details>
    </div>

